1. Introduction

In this project work, we will analyze three datasets. The first one: Wholesale Customers is used to conduct techniques for Unsupervised Learning. The second one: Real Estate Valuation is used to conduct techniques for Regression. The third one: Red Wine Quality is used to conduct techniques for Classification.

2. Data

2a. Wholesale Customers: Unsupervised Learning

This dataset has been taken from UCI repository and uses clients of wholesale distributor. For several products the dataset represents numeric values of spending. The target varaible is considered to be regions.

Data set can be downloaded here: https://archive.ics.uci.edu/dataset/292/wholesale+customers

Explanatory variables:

1 - Fresh

2 - Milk

3 - Grocery

4 - Frozen

5 - Detergents_Paper

6 - Delicassen

Dependent varaible:

7 - Region

2b. Real Estate Valuation: Regression

This dataset has been taken from UCI repository and includes the data of real estate valuation that will be analyzed further.

Explanatory variables:

1 - X1 transaction date

2 - X2 house age

3 - X3 distance to the nearest MRT station

4 - X4 number of convenience stores

5 - X5 latitude

6 - X6 longitude

Dependent varaible:

7 - Y house price of unit area

Data set can be downloaded here: https://archive.ics.uci.edu/dataset/477/real+estate+valuation+data+set

2c. Red Wine Quality: Classification

This dataset has been taken from UCI repository and includes the data from red wine samples that will be further analysed. It consists out of wines chemical components that will be considered as explanatory variables and wine quality rated on a scale to 10 that will be treated as dependent variable.

Data set can be downloaded here: https://archive.ics.uci.edu/dataset/186/wine+quality

Explanatory variables:

1 - fixed acidity

2 - volatile acidity

3 - citric acid

4 - residual sugar

5 - chlorides

6 - free sulfur dioxide

7 - total sulfur dioxide

8 - density

9 - pH

10 - sulphates

11 - alcohol

Dependent varaible:

12 - quality (score between 0 and 10)

3. Aims of the research

For the unsupervised learning task:

  1. Condut K-Means to divide dataset into K clusters with the nearest means to get insights on customers purchasing behaviour.

  2. Conduct Principal Component Analysis for the dimensionality reduction while saving the crucial information. Assess the model.

For the regression task:

  1. Divide the data on training and test sets, build Linear regression model, assess the performance.

  2. Divide the data on training and test sets, build Random forest model, assess the performance.

For the classification task:

  1. Divide the data on training and test sets, build Multinomial logistic regression model, assess the performance.

  2. Divide the data on training and test sets, build K-Nearest Neighbor model, assess the performance.

4. Unsupervised Learning Task (Wholesale Customers)

Identify homogeneous population groups and dimension reduction techniques for wholesale customer dataset. We decided to exclude Channel and Region, as categorical variabels may not work well on distance based algorithms.

4a. K-Means Clustering

Conduct K-Means to divide dataset into K clusters with the nearest means. First, we need to identify the number of K. We will use The Elbow Method.

# Remove 'Channel' and 'Region' variables from the dataset
wholesale_data_without_cat <- wholesale_data[, !(names(wholesale_data) %in% c("Channel", "Region"))]

# Compute the within-cluster sum of squares (WCSS) for different values of K
wcss <- vector()
for (i in 1:10) {
  kmeans_model <- kmeans(wholesale_data_without_cat, centers = i, nstart = 10)
  wcss[i] <- kmeans_model$tot.withinss
}

# Plot the elbow method graph
plot(1:10, wcss, type = 'b', pch = 19, frame = FALSE, xlab = 'Number of Clusters (K)', ylab = 'Within-cluster Sum of Squares (WCSS)', main = 'Elbow Method')

The elbow point is K=5, where the slope gets flatter.

# Fit K-means model with k=5
kmeans_model <- kmeans(wholesale_data_without_cat, centers = 5, nstart = 10)

# Get cluster assignments for each observation
cluster_assignments <- kmeans_model$cluster

# View the cluster centers
cluster_centers <- kmeans_model$centers
print(cluster_centers)

# Calculate average spending for each product category within each cluster

4b. Principal Component Analysis

Lets conduct PCA, where we will use a scree plot to decide on the number of PC

# Perform PCA
pca_result <- prcomp(wholesale_data[, -c(1, 2)], scale. = TRUE)

# Summary of PCA results
summary(pca_result)
## Importance of components:
##                           PC1    PC2    PC3     PC4     PC5    PC6
## Standard deviation     1.6263 1.3048 0.8603 0.75082 0.53449 0.2509
## Proportion of Variance 0.4408 0.2838 0.1233 0.09396 0.04761 0.0105
## Cumulative Proportion  0.4408 0.7246 0.8479 0.94189 0.98950 1.0000
# Scree plot
plot(1:length(pca_result$sdev), pca_result$sdev^2 / sum(pca_result$sdev^2), type = "b", 
     xlab = "Principal Component", ylab = "Proportion of Variance Explained", 
     main = "Scree Plot")

By the elbow point we dicde to choose PCA with 4 PC

# Perform PCA with 4 principal components
num_pcs <- 4
pca_result <- prcomp(wholesale_data[, -c(1, 2)], scale. = TRUE, rank = num_pcs)

# Summary of PCA results
summary(pca_result)

# Create a better biplot with "PC1" and "PC2" labels

Here is the distribution of customers on the first 2 PC

# Perform PCA with 4 principal components
pca_result <- prcomp(wholesale_data[, -c(1, 2)], scale. = TRUE, rank = 4)

# Perform K-means clustering on the first two principal components
kmeans_result <- kmeans(pca_result$x[, 1:2], centers = 5)
cluster_assignments <- kmeans_result$cluster

# Plot PCA of customer segments with colors representing clusters
plot(pca_result$x[, 1], pca_result$x[, 2], col = cluster_assignments, 
     pch = 16, xlab = "PC1", ylab = "PC2", main = "PCA Plot with Clusters")

# Add legend
legend("topright", legend = unique(cluster_assignments), col = 1:max(cluster_assignments), pch = 16, title = "Cluster")

{# Calculate the proportion of variance explained by each principal component
prop_var <- pca_result$sdev^2 / sum(pca_result$sdev^2)
}

Model Assessment

# Create a table to display proportions of variance explained by each principal component
var_table <- data.frame(
  Principal_Component = paste("PC", 1:length(prop_var)),
  Variance_Explained = prop_var

Performing Linear Regression technique by dividing data into training and test sets.

# Load required library
library(caret)
## Loading required package: lattice
# Set seed for reproducibility
set.seed(123)

# Split the dataset into 80% training and 20% test sets
train_index <- createDataPartition(real_estate_data$`Y house price of unit area`, p = 0.8, list = FALSE)
train_data <- real_estate_data[train_index, ]
test_data <- real_estate_data[-train_index, ]

# Fit a linear regression model using the training data
lm_model <- lm(`Y house price of unit area` ~ ., data = train_data)

# Make predictions on the test data
predictions <- predict(lm_model, newdata = test_data)

# Evaluate the model's performance
mse <- mean((test_data$`Y house price of unit area` - predictions)^2)
rmse <- sqrt(mse)
print(paste("Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE):", rmse))
## [1] "Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE): 7.78379778126903"

summary(lm_model)

5b. Random Forest

Performing Random Forest technique, by dividing data into training and test sets as the opposite to Linear Regression to capture nonlinear relationship.

# Load the randomForest package
library(randomForest)
## randomForest 4.7-1.1
## Type rfNews() to see new features/changes/bug fixes.
## 
## Attaching package: 'randomForest'
## The following object is masked from 'package:ggplot2':
## 
##     margin
# Split the data into features (X) and target variable (Y)
X <- real_estate_data[, -1]  # Exclude 'No' column
Y <- real_estate_data$`Y house price of unit area`

# Split data into training and testing sets (80% training data)
set.seed(123)  # for reproducibility
train_index <- sample(1:nrow(X), 0.8 * nrow(X))  # 80% training data
X_train <- X[train_index, ]
Y_train <- Y[train_index]
X_test <- X[-train_index, ]
Y_test <- Y[-train_index]

# Train the random forest regression model
rf_model <- randomForest(x = X_train, y = Y_train)

# Predict the target variable for the test dataset
Y_pred <- predict(rf_model, newdata = X_test)

# Calculate RMSE
rmse <- sqrt(mean((Y_pred - Y_test)^2))
print(paste("Root Mean Squared Error (RF):", rmse))
## [1] "Root Mean Squared Error (RF): 2.20670981444569"

Visualization of Actual vs.Predicted Quality.

# Visualize actual vs predicted house prices for regression
plot(Y_pred, Y_test,
     xlab = "Predicted Price",
     ylab = "Actual Price",
     main = "Actual vs Predicted House Prices for Regression",
     pch = 16, col = "blue")
abline(0, 1, col = "red")

Visualization of Feature Importance.

# Train the random forest regression model
rf_model <- randomForest(x = X_train, y = Y_train)

# Calculate variable importance
var_importance <- importance(rf_model)

# Create a dot plot for variable importance
dotchart(var_importance, main = "Variable Importance Plot", col = "black", pch = 19)

6. Classification Task (Red Wine Quality)

Utilize classification techniques to investigate, quantify, and predict the relationship between chemical properties of wine and wine quality categories

6a. Multinomial Logistic Regression

Performing Multinomial Logistic Regression technique by dividing data into training and test sets, and dividing quality into 4 classes:Poor, Fair, Good, Excellent. Evaluate the prediction.

Precision-Recall Curve

# Assuming multinom_model is your multinomial logistic regression model

# Make predictions on test data to obtain predicted probabilities for each class
probabilities <- predict(multinom_model, newdata = test_data, type = "probs")

# Calculate precision, recall, and thresholds for each class
precision <- numeric()
recall <- numeric()
thresholds <- seq(0, 1, by = 0.01)

for (threshold in thresholds) {
  # Convert predicted probabilities to binary predictions based on threshold
  binary_predictions <- apply(probabilities, 2, function(x) ifelse(x >= threshold, 1, 0))
  
  # Calculate precision and recall for each class
  class_precision <- c()
  class_recall <- c()
  for (i in 1:ncol(binary_predictions)) {
    tp <- sum(binary_predictions[, i] == 1 & test_data$quality == levels(test_data$quality)[i])
    fp <- sum(binary_predictions[, i] == 1 & test_data$quality != levels(test_data$quality)[i])
    fn <- sum(binary_predictions[, i] == 0 & test_data$quality == levels(test_data$quality)[i])
    class_precision[i] <- tp / (tp + fp)
    class_recall[i] <- tp / (tp + fn)
  }
  
  # Take the mean precision and recall across all classes
  precision <- c(precision, mean(class_precision))
  recall <- c(recall, mean(class_recall))
}

# Plot Precision-Recall curve
library(ggplot2)
df <- data.frame(thresholds, precision, recall)
ggplot(df, aes(x = recall, y = precision)) +
  geom_line() +
  geom_point() +
  labs(x = "Recall", y = "Precision", title = "Precision-Recall Curve")
## Warning: Removed 64 rows containing missing values or values outside the scale range
## (`geom_line()`).
## Warning: Removed 64 rows containing missing values or values outside the scale range
## (`geom_point()`).

6b. K-Nearest Neighbors

Performing K-Nearest Neighbor technique by dividing data into training and test sets, and dividing quality into 4 classes:Poor, Fair, Good, Excellent. Evaluate the prediction.

First, lets explore different values of K and apply the one which gives the highest accuracy

library(class)
library(caret)
library(ggplot2)

# Preprocess the data: Convert quality to categorical classes
wine_quality$quality_class <- cut(wine_quality$quality, breaks = c(0, 5, 6, 7, 10),
                                  labels = c("Poor", "Fair", "Good", "Excellent"))

# Split data into training and testing sets (80% training, 20% testing)
set.seed(123)  # for reproducibility
train_indices <- createDataPartition(wine_quality$quality_class, p = 0.8, list = FALSE)
train_data <- wine_quality[train_indices, ]
test_data <- wine_quality[-train_indices, ]

# Define a range of k values to try
k_values <- seq(1, 20, by = 2)

# Initialize vectors to store accuracy values for each k
accuracy_values <- vector()

# Iterate over each k value
for (k in k_values) {
  # Train KNN classifier
  knn_model <- knn(train = train_data[, -c(12, 13)], test = test_data[, -c(12, 13)],
                   cl = train_data$quality_class, k = k)
  
  # Evaluate performance
  accuracy <- mean(knn_model == test_data$quality_class)
  accuracy_values <- c(accuracy_values, accuracy)
}

# Visualize the results
results <- data.frame(k = k_values, accuracy = accuracy_values)
ggplot(results, aes(x = k, y = accuracy)) +
  geom_line() +
  geom_point() +
  labs(title = "Accuracy vs. Number of Neighbors (K)",
       x = "Number of Neighbors (K)", y = "Accuracy") +
  theme_minimal()

We can see that K=5 gives the highest accuracy, so we choose it (do not choose K<5 due to high variance and class imbalance problems.) 

# Load required libraries
library(class)
library(caret)
library(ggplot2)

# Preprocess the data: Convert quality to categorical classes
wine_quality$quality_class <- cut(wine_quality$quality, breaks = c(0, 5, 6, 7, 10),
                                  labels = c("Poor", "Fair", "Good", "Excellent"))

# Split data into training and testing sets (80% training, 20% testing)
set.seed(123)  # for reproducibility
train_indices <- createDataPartition(wine_quality$quality_class, p = 0.8, list = FALSE)
train_data <- wine_quality[train_indices, ]
test_data <- wine_quality[-train_indices, ]

# Train KNN classifier
k <- 5  # Number of neighbors
knn_model <- knn(train = train_data[, -c(12, 13)], test = test_data[, -c(12, 13)],
                 cl = train_data$quality_class, k = k)

# Evaluate performance
accuracy <- mean(knn_model == test_data$quality_class)
cat("Accuracy of KNN classifier:", accuracy, "\n")
## Accuracy of KNN classifier: 0.5425868
# Visualize decision boundaries (for two selected features)
feature1 <- "alcohol"
feature2 <- "volatile.acidity"

# Create a grid of points to predict
x1 <- seq(min(wine_quality[[feature1]]), max(wine_quality[[feature1]]), length.out = 100)
x2 <- seq(min(wine_quality[[feature2]]), max(wine_quality[[feature2]]), length.out = 100)
grid <- expand.grid(alcohol = x1, volatile.acidity = x2)

# Predict classes for the grid points
grid$predicted_class <- knn(train = train_data[, c(feature1, feature2)],
                            test = grid, cl = train_data$quality_class, k = k)

# Plot the decision boundaries
ggplot(data = grid, aes(x = alcohol, y = volatile.acidity, color = predicted_class)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.5) +
  geom_point(data = test_data, aes(x = alcohol, y = volatile.acidity), color = "black", size = 2) +
  labs(title = "Decision Boundaries for KNN Classifier",
       x = "Alcohol", y = "Volatile Acidity", color = "Predicted Class") +
  theme_minimal()

3. Conclusion

  1. For unsupervised learning:

The proportion of variance explained by PC is as follows:

PC1 explains approximately 44.08% of the variance.

PC2 explains approximately 28.38% of the variance.

PC3 explains approximately 12.33% of the variance.

PC4 explains approximately 9.40% of the variance.

PC5 explains approximately 4.76% of the variance.

PC6 explains approximately 1.05% of the variance.

  1. For regression, RMSE(Random forest) = 2.21 < RMSE(Linear Regression) = 7.79. So we prefer Random forest.

  2. For classification, Accuracy(KNN) = 0.54 < Accuracy(Multinomial Logit) = 0.61. So we prefer Multinomial logistic regression.
